Dr. Spatz,<br><br>
Check your last message. I mirrored your spelling.<br><br>
By the way, I haven't had to suffer the poor housing, low paying jobs and other problems vets have had to suffer.<br><br>
I have made every effort to make something of my life after Vietnam and since then.<br><br>
Maybe you need to talk to the men and women that served, fought and returned home. Only to have to fight the people here just to get a job in the mid 70's.<br><br>
I didn't get drafted. I enlisted because I felt it was the right thing to do. A nation was trying to free itself from communism. I was not a politician nor was I an educated idiot hiding behind wealth or social standing. I came from a lower middle class family that struggled to make ends meet.<br><br>
The chip I have on my shoulder are peolpe like you that won't give men like me the opportunities to advance forward because our views differ from yours.<br><br>
There were over 2 million soldiers sent to Vietnam. 58 thousand didn't come back alive. They are remembered on walls around the nation not for fighting in an unjust war. They are remembered for the sacrifices they each made. Thier politics didn't make a difference in their death. Your politics won't matter when you die.<br><br>
Look back at the history of the protesting that took place n campuses all over this nation. Buildings were destroyed. National Guardsmen were attacted and lives were lost. By your own standard, it was perfectly alright for the students to burn down buildings belonging to the ROTC and to attack the National Guardsmen. I say they were wrong in their action. Just as wrong as the Guardsmen were when the shots werre fired. But why attack or destroy poeple and property when niether had anything to do with our being sent to Vietnam?<br><br>
I restate my stand that had the actions of the protestors been directed to the politicians that sent us there instead of at us the soldier, I would have joined your efforts.<br><br>
You have every right to believe the way you do but that does not give you the right to pawn your veiws as absolute and righteous. This sight is not for only you to post those ideals. I absolutely do not agree that breaking the law is a valid excuse to defend any viewpoint.<br><br>
There were those that did protest the war in a legal manner and those folks I admire because they did not bow down to the mob-like mentality of mindless cows that would follow the leader of the herd over a cliff.<br><br>
So if you don't like my opinion of your views, that's too bad. I can accept your right your view and I will always give that priviledge to voice it. I expect the same from you.
